<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:1<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I25623f80630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>A.</label.designator><headtext>Subpoenas; Attendance</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05aa682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:1.</label.designator><headtext>Authority to compel attendance</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Citizens are granted the right to testify under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018074" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST1-2-6" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icaa7b1107fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 1-2-6</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The courts have inherent authority to compel witness attendance. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018074" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-13-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icaa7b1117fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 24-13-21</cite.query> to <cite.query w-src-number="0287018074" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-13-29" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icaa7b1127fbf11ea988285db8533e975">24-13-29</cite.query> apply to the courts, but specific legislation has granted subpoena power to other administrative or legislative bodies as well. <eos/><bos/>These bodies may need the court to compel witness attendance.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1355e107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] In 1976, the Georgia Supreme Court reviewed the history of subpoena law in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018074" w-serial-number="1977196753" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icaa8c2827fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Brown v. State</ital></cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1355e117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic1355e107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Under the Georgia Administrative Procedure Act, an agency or a hearing officer may issue subpoenas, but must apply to the Superior Court for an order to compel obedience if a witness fails to comply. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018074" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST50-13-13" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icaa826407fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 50-13-13(a)(6), (7)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1355e117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018074" w-serial-number="1977196753" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icaa8e9927fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Brown v. State, 238 Ga. 98, 231 S.E.2d 65 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:1<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
